–Afdød","1260–Male":"1260–Afdød","1262–Female":"1262–Afdød","1457":"1457","1398":"1398","1376":"1376","ABT    1295":"omkring 1295","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1262":"1262","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","of,,Merionethshire,Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"ABT    1295–Deceased":"circa 1295–Overleden","1295–Male":"1295–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1376–Female":"1376–Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1396–1457":"1396–1457","1398–Female":"1398–Overleden","1260–Male":"1260–Overleden","1262–Female":"1262–Overleden","1457":"1457","1398":"1398","1376":"1376","ABT    1295":"circa 1295","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1262":"1262","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","of,,Merionethshire,Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT    1295–Deceased":"about 1295–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1376–Female":"1376–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1396–1457":"1396–1457","1398–Female":"1398–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1262–Female":"1262–Deceased","1457":"1457","1398":"1398","1376":"1376","ABT    1295":"about 1295","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1262":"1262","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","of,,Merionethshire,Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"Leia\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Leah ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘languid’ in Hebrew), borne by the elder sister of Rachel (Genesis 29:23). Jacob served her father Laban for seven years in return for the hand of Rachel, but was deceived into marrying Leah first. He was then given Rachel as well, but had to labour seven more years afterwards. For a long time the name was mainly Jewish, although it also enjoyed some favour among the Puritans in the 16th century. It was taken up again in the 1980s and has been widely popular since the 1990s."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn \" Leia\" ap Llywelyn was born about 1295, in Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Llywelyn ap Madog, was 37 and his mother, Angharad Ferch Lorwerth, was 35. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Amabl ferch Dafydd."},"et":{"ABT    1295–Deceased":"umbes 1295–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud"